{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930110101/0425.xml":{"full_text":"David Belasco Opens His Latest Production Here\nNEW BELASCO\nPLAY OPENS\nMONDAY\nA new Belasco production, al\nways a matter of dramatic im\nportance, is scheduled for the\nShubert Belasco Theater on Mon\nday night when Mr. Belasco will\npresent his second production of\nthe season. The new play, \u201cTo\nnight or Never\u201d was written by\nLili Hatvany, the author of \u201cThe\nLove Duel.\u201d\nMiss Hatvany has evolved a\nnovel and unique play and under\nthe able direction of Mr. Belasco\nshould prove a happy dramatic\nevent for the theater lovers of\nthis city,\nThe play will mark Mr.\nBelasco\u2019s 375th production, a long\nand honorable record which no\ndoubt will never be surpased.\nFor the central character in\nthe new play, Mr. Belasco has\nbeen Indeed fortunate in securing\nthe services of Helen Gahagan.\nMiss Gahagan has been in Italy\nstudying music for the past three\nyears, having abandoned the\nstage in 1928 to embark on a\ncontemplated operatic career.\nShe sang in gala performances in\nCentral Europe during the past\nspring and summer but cancelled\nall other engagements when Mr.\nBelasco finally persuaded her to\nreturn to America and take up\nthe new role. Although the play\n18 written around the life of an\nopera star, Mr. Belasco is the\nauthority for the statement that\nthe plot does not concern the\ntemperament and tantrums of an\nopera prima donna but it is a\nplay that will rely solely on its\nlove story and dramatic interest.\nAlways most careful in the\nselection of his casts, Mr. Belasco\nbegan seeking artists for his new\nplay months ago. He interviewed\nmany well known players and\nthat his work has not been m\nvain is evident by the exceptional\ncast which he has selected to sup\nport Miss Gahagan, which in\ncludes such well known artists\nas Melvyn Douglas, Ferdinand\nGottschalk, Warburton Gamble,\nRobert Greig, Katherine Stewart,\nGreta Meyer and Edmund Loewe.\nMRS. FISKE IN\nTHACKERAY\nDRAMA\nA glorious evening for the old\nguard of the guild of theater\ngoers was vouchsafed last evening\nat the Rapley-Cochran playhouse\nwhen Mrs. Fiske entered upon\nthe final lap of her repertoire\n\u25a0week with a revival of \u201cBecky\nSharp.\u201d\nThe glamour of the play re\nmains, even. though age has\ndimmed its brilliance; and the\ngreat player who created the role\nof the immortal adventures of\nThackeray js still in the forefront\nof the American theater, linking\nthe new generation to the old\nmore effectively, pernaps, than\nany other actress.\nThe procession of these pic\nturesque Victorian characters\u2014\nRawdon Crawley, with the ghost\nof Maurice Barrymore in the\nshadow of the role; the Marquis\nof Steyne, Sir Pitt Crawley, Jos\nSedley. Lady Crawley, the whole\ncast of \u201cVanity Fair\u201d\u2014was suffi\ncient to make the presentation\nlast night one of the real high\nlights of the season.\nSuffice it to that the perform\nance was excellent; that Mrs.\nFiske disported herself in what\nis in many respects the greatest\nrole of her career; and that\n\"Becky Efharp\u201d will be repeated\nat the National this afternoon\nand evening. A word to the\nwise is sufficient.\nLittle Showing a\n'Men Only Film'\n\u201cUnguarded Girls,\u201d which\nplayed to capacity audiences at\nthe Little Theater all this week,\nwill begin showing for men only,\nSunday, with added features.\n\u201cUnguarded Girls\u201d has caused\nconsiderable talk wherever it has\nbeen shown. The Police Depart\nment and police officials co-oper\nated in making this sensational\ndrama of Vice conditions. The\npicture has to do with the police\ndepartment\u2019s \u201cBureau of Missing\nPersons,\u201d which tells the tragic\nstory of many girls reported\nmissing in a large city. The\nfilm pictures with graphic details\npitfalls and vice snares that await\nthe inexperienced girl.\nThis will be the last week of\nthe showing in Washington and\ntherefore the only opportunity\nfor the men to see this attrac\ntion which played at the Earl\nCarroll Theater, New York, for\n12 weeks.\n-NOW SHOWING-\nIASI THE\nLONE WOLf\nBERT LYTELL\nPATSY WITH MIUfA\n-fQI\u00bb Q(Mtd Qttracfionj\nI /n ~New ~Belasco Play\naHBf\nIF vSC -v.\u2019----'-\nMMMK HI\nBf'\nJ s -W\n'W\n11\n\u25a0gp V\nUh\nHELEN GAHAGAN, star of \u201cTonight or Never,\u201d the\nnew Lili Hatvany play which will have its first perform\nance at the Belasco Theater Monday night under the\naegis of the venerable David Belasco. The producer will\nbe here in person for the premiere.\nThrilling Subway Murder\n\u201cSubway Express,\u201d in the front<\nrank of mystery plays produced\nlast season, will begin a week\u2019s\nengagement at the National The\nater Monday night with the usual\nWednesday and Saturday mati\nnees.\nOs all the detective thrillers\nproduced last season this opus\nof the subway by Eva Kay Flint\nand Martha Madison proved to\nbe the only one to suiwive.\nTherefore it lived and prospered\nfor eight months in New York.\nIt is a novel show, devoid of the\nclap-trap common to most thrill\ners and it never cheats.\nIt tells a straightforward story\nand the entire action takes place\nin a moving subway train, and\nit is capitally acted by a cast\nof about 40.\nWashingtonians will be quick\nto applaud the novel setting, for\nit\u2019s an exact replica of a New\nYork subway car. This car\nmoves, rattles past local stations\nand makes the express stops.\nPassengers crowd in and depart\nat every stop. Lights blink and\nthrough the open windows you see\npassing trains. In this novel stage\nsetting you see all types, the\nkind you will find in any under\nground railway. You find the\nloud-voiced small merchant, flap\npers and sheiks, and the motley\ncrowd that uses the subway. Into\nthis crowded car comes two Wall\nStreet men and the wife of one\nof them.\nThere is a scuffle at Times\nSquare, a shot is fired and one of\nthe Wall Street brokers is killed.\nThe police arrive, hold everyone\nin the car, and then comes In\nspector Hannen, the role played\nby Leo Curley.\nThis police inspector is a suave\nindividual, plain spoken and\nadroit at his profession. He sus\npects he has been summoned\non an errand that any uniformed\ncop ought to be able to handle\nbut when a medical examiner\nappears he finds he has a first\nSEE IT NOW OR NEVER\nLAST 2 TIMES\nTARAV Matinee at 2:30 P.M.\nI UUM T~ TONIGHT at 8:15\nWASHINGTON AUDITORIUM\n77te Original Freiburg\nNow On Its First American Tour With\nADOLF FASSNACHT\nWorld F amour CHRISTUS Portrayor\nDirect From Germany and the N. Y. Hippodrome\nNight Prices. 50c to 33.00. Sat. Mat., s\u00abe to 32.00.\nALL SEATS RESERVED FOR ALL PERFORMANCES.\nTICKETS ON SALE\u2014Waahlaartoa Auditorium. Phone Nat. 3135. Tal\nbert Theatre Ticket Acency, Willard Hotel, Phonea National 5573-70,\n4430. T. Arthur Smith. H. L. Kitt Maale Co, Phone Nat. 3700. AAA\nTHE SPOKEN DRAMA\u2014NOT A MOTION PICTURE\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nrate murder mystery on his\nhands. Before he solves it an\nother man loses his life. This\nall happens in front of the\naudience and they become as\nmystified as the police. With\nthe flashing lights, passing sta\ntions and intensely exciting situa\ntions, it is all first rate theater\nand mighty realistic.\nThe humor of the piece, and\nthere are many hearty laughs\nthroughout the play, is not\ndragged in just for laughs, but\nis part of the story. Every bit\nis acted for all it is worth. As\nthe police inspector, Leo Curley\ngives a fine performance of a\ndifficult role. Others in the\ncast are Jack Byrne, Virginia\nCurley, Hugh Duffy, Marie Pet\ntis, William T. Hayes, Edward\nEverett Hale. Wall Spence, Ralph\nSimone, Maude Nolan, and many\nothers.\nBert Lytell In Film\nRole He Made Famous\nOnce again Bert Lytell is to\nbe seen in the role he made\nfamous on the screen, that of\nthe master mind whose bouts of\nwits with the gendarmes always\nresulted in the devastating fail\nure of the forces of the law to\nhold him for any length of time.\nBut in his latest picture, \u2018*The\nLast of the Lone Wolf,\u201d which\nis to be found at Warner Bros.\nMetropolitan Theater this week,\nthe well-mannered crook is at\nlast out for the count\u2014and it is\nCupid who stings him hard.\nGAYETY THEATRE\nIthtF\u00dfh. Phone Diftt. 9324\nWashington\u2019s Only Burlesque\nTheater\nNEXT WEEK\njerri McCauley\nATTRACTIONS\nON WAY TO\nTHEATERS\nThe two champion \u2018\u2018show\nstealers\u201d of the, entire motion pic\nture Industry have been teamed\ntogether and are headed toward\nthe Columbia as the attraction to\nsucceed \u201cWhoopee.\u201d\nThe two players are none other\nthan Marie Dressier and Wallace\nBeery, co-starring in \"Min and\nBill.\u201d It is a known fact that\nMarie Dressier walked off with\nthe honors in \u201cWar Out West\u201d\nand \u201cLet Us Be Gay.\u201d On the\nother hand, the honors went to\nWallace Beery in \"Big House.\u201d\n\"Way for a Sailor\u201d and \u201cBilly\nthe Kid.\u201d\nGilbert Miller\u2019s first production\nof the current season, \u201cMar\nseilles,\u201d will be presented at the\nShubert-Belasco Theater the week\nof November 10.\nThe play is from the pen of\nMarcel Pagnol and had a most\nspectacular success abroad. It is\na tale of the city and of the\nsea and promises to become as\npopular as his \u201cTopaze,\u201d in which\nFrank Morgan has been delight\ning New York audiences for past\nmonth's. Alexander Kirkland, Dud\nley Digges and Alison Skipworth,\nforemost in a cast of notable\nplayers, have been chosen by Mr.\nMiller for the Ameritan premiere.\nWalter Huston and Kay Francis,\nin \u201cThe Virtuous Sin,\u201d will oe the\nnext attraction at Loew\u2019s Palace\nTheater.\nRex Beach\u2019s \u201cThe Silver Horde,\nwith Louis Wolheim and Evelyn\nBrent, will be the next screen\nattraction at R-K-O-Keith\u2019s.\nGeorge M. Cohan in his first\nnation-wide tour of \u201cThe Tavern\u2019\u2019\nis announced at the National\nTheater for the week of Novem\nber 10. He will be seen in the\nrole of the Vagabond in this cel\nebrated satire of old-time melo\ndramas.\n\u201cThe Tavern\u201d was revived in\nNew York at the Fulton Theater\nlast spring and virtually the same\nplayers as seen in the play at\nthat time are associated with Mr.\nCohan in this noteworthy tour.\nIt will be recalled that \u201cThe\nTavern\u201d was first hurled upon an\nunsuspecting audience in New\nYork in September, 1920. Even\nthe critics were baffled. Not until\nthe final act, in which the mad\nness of the whole thing was re\nvealed, did many of the reviewers\nsuspect that Georgie Cohan was\npoking fun at the old school of\nmystery theater.\n\u201cLove In the Rough.\u201d a comedy\nof the golf links, and Tom Patri\ncola and the Brox Sisters are the\nscreen and stage features to be\npresented at Warner\u2019s Earle for\nthe week starting Saturday, No\nvember 8. Robert Montgomery,\nDorothy Jordan, Benny Rubin\nand Dorothy McNulty have the\nleading roles in the screen fea\nture. Supplementing Tom Patri\ncola and the Three Brox Sisters\non the stage are the Pearl Twins.\nWillie West and McGinty and\nother acts.\nWinnie Lightner in her latest\ncomedy, \u201cThe Life of the Party.\u201d\nwill play a return engagement\nin downtown Washington when\nthat Warner Bros, and Vitaphone\nproduction opens another week\u2019s\nengagement on Friday. Novem\nber 7, at Warner\u2019s Metropolitan.\nWarner Baxter in \u201cRenegades\u201d\nis the Fox Theater\u2019s contribution\nto Washington amusement start\ning Friday. \u201cRenegades\u201d is a\nForeign Legion story, done in an\nentirely different manner. Noah\nBeery, George Cooper and Myrna\nLoy make up the supporting\ncast.\nR-K-O KEITH\u2019S\nHELD OVER\n2\u2014WEEK/\nBy Tremendous Popular Demand!\nOUTSHINING THEIR GLORY\nON ~HE RADIO\n\u2014Z\u2014\u2014__\nM I *4 J/\na\u2122 W\nDOUBLE CHECK vw\n(A Radio Picture)\n\u201cIRRESISTIBLE\u201d say idolizing Washingtonians as\nthey throb and come to life in their first all talking\nfeature picture.\nIT NO ADVANCE IN PRICES -W\nTho National Daily\nEDMUND LOWE\nIN GRIPPING\nMOVIE\nThere is something strangely\ngripping about this week's feature\nattraction at the Fox\u2014\" Scotland\nYard.\u201d One could no more get up\nand leave before the finish than\none could quit a world series game\nin the eighth inning with the score\ntied.\nBut what there is about this pic-\nJOAN BENNETT lUnt.\nEdmund Lowe is cast as the\ncrook and reveals acting capabili\nties never hitherto suspected. He\nhas the nonchalance of a first\nclass raffles. He finds himself\nin most embarrassing situations\nbut never for a minute loses the\nperfect poise of the gentleman\ncrook. He plays the dual role of\nDakin Barrolles, the bank thief,\nwho enlists in the British army\nto escape Scotland Yard, and Sir\nJohn Lasher, a banker. Barrolles\nthrough a miracle of plastic sur\ngery is given the face of Sir John\nLasher and assumes the\nidentity, even deceiving the wife\nof the banker, who, as is custo\nmary in the movies, falls in love\nwith the raffles.\nScotland Yard eventually\ncatches up with the crook but\nthere are a number of diverting\nincidents that make the chase\nhighly interesting.\nCharming Joan Bennett Is cast\nas the banker\u2019s wife and lends\ntone and distinction to the pic\nture. The other characters, Don\nald Crisp, Barrolles\u2019 accomplice,\nand Lumsden Hare as Sir Clive\nof Scotland Yard, are well cast.\nThe Fanchon and Marco idea\nof the week is entitled a \u201cBox\nof Candy.\u201d Reeves and Lou in\na doll dance are probably the\nbest of the lot of entertainers.\nJones and Hull and Molino and\nDavis, comedians, are mildly\namusing, Lynn Cowan, song\nwriter, and Marie. Lucy and Irene\nin specialty numbers also strive\nto entertain.\nThe second of the \u201cStrange As\nIt Seems\u201d series by John Hix\nhas lots of variety and spice. Fox\nMovietone has an encouraging\nstraight from the shoulder talk\nby Merle Thorpe on the return\nof prosperity.\nDirector Setter Is a\n\u2018Send It By Wire\u2019 Fan\nDirector William A. Se 11 e r\nshares with Florenz Ziegfeld the\ndistinction of being the most\nprolific telegram writer in the\nworld. For \u201cThe Truth About\nYouth\u201d alone. First National\u2019s\nnew picture with Loretta Young,\nDavid Manners, Conway Tearle\nand Myrna Loy, current at War\nner Bros. Earle Theater, Seiter\nsent over 400 telegrams and\nthree cables.\nThe telegrams ranged from one\nasking B. Harrison Orkow, who\nwrote the script and who Was\nin New York during the shoot\ning. if certain changes would not\nimprove the story, to anothei\nasking a friend in Chicago to\nsend an original copy of the\nstage play, \u201cWhen We Were\nTwenty-one\u201d that he had stored\nin a private vault. The cables\nwere for verification of the plans\nof a night club that is a copy\nof the Ciro Playground in Paris.\nSATURDAY\u2014NOVEMBER 1\u20141930\nture that makes\nit so fascinatr\ning is difficult\nto explain. The\nstory is some\nwhat unusual\nbut often im\nplausible and\nthe outcome of\nthe plot easy to\nenvision. Per\nhap its the fas\ncination of Scot\nland Yard and\nall that the\nname betokens,\nthe relentless,\nunceasing man-\nA million letters from the pens\nof followers from Portland to\nPhoenix, from Tampa to Taco\nma, were responsible for the film\ning of Amos \u2019n\u2019 Andy\u2019s first talk\ning picture, \u201cCheck and Double\nCheck.\u201d It marks the first time\nthat a picture has been filmed\ndirectly in response to letters\nfrom the public.\n\u201cWe\u2019ve heard Amos, \u2019n\u2019 Andy\nso much...We must see them!\u201d\nWas the substance of the vast\nflood of mail. \u201cWhy not put\ntheir radio story into a talking\npicture?\u201d\n\u201cCheck and Double ChecK,\u201d\nproduced by Radio Pictures, is\nthe result. Local audiences now\nhave their first chance to see\nthese two radio. kings at R-K O\nKeith\u2019s where the picture has\nbeen held over for a second week\nto accommodate the thousands\nof fans desiring to see them on\nthe screen.\nThe influx of those tons of\nfan letters to Amos \u2019n\u2019 Andy in\ncare of the National Broadcast\ning company was the signal for\nspirited bidding on the part of\npractically every film producer.\nThe famous kings of the air fi\nnally accepted a contract with\nRadio Pictures.\nGuided by the fans\u2019 prepon\nderant preference to see Amos\n\u2019n\u2019 Andy in the same characteri\nzations and meeting the same\nproblems that form the basis of\ntheir daily radio sketches, the\nproducers have not altered the\nAmos \u2019n\u2019 Andy that millions have\nlearned to love. Their associated\ncharacters also have been re\ntained who play important parts\nin the picture. That remark\nably ramshackle vehicle, the\nFresh Air Taxicab, makes its\nfirst screen appearance and au-\nIto SIN IS \u20ac>l\nHUMAN f\nBUT WHO\nH IS TO BLAME\nv\nW\u00ae J\nill f\n9%e LEOPARD\nreveals his\nSPOTS 7\nr*r' ,^'i^ >s\ni\nV 4/fli\nHr\n=HAROLD BELL f\ng WRIGHT\u2019S\nEl yi\nI RIALTO i\nNOW PLAYING\nKingfish and Andy\n\\\\i i VjMVH\nRUSSELL POWELL (the Kingfish), is regusted with\nBrudder Andy\u2014a scene from the Amos \u2019n\u2019 Andy picture,\n\u201cCheck and Double Check,\u201d which is now packing in the\npatrons at R-K-0 Keith\u2019s, and is held for a second week.\nFan Letters Made Stars\ndiences taken within the\nsacred lodge rooms of the Mys\ntic Knights of the Sea, a whole\nshow within itself.\nA brilliant cast of players is\nseen in support of Amos \u2019n\u2019 Andy,\nincluding Irene Rich, Sue Carol,\nCharles Morton, Ralf Harolde\nand Rita La\u00dfoy. Melville Brown\ndirected the original story by\nBert Kalmar and Harry Ruby.\nTearle\u2019s List\nConway Tearle, featured with\nLoretta Young, David Menners\nand Myrna Loy, at Warner\nBrothers Earle Theater in First\nNational\u2019s \"Truth About Youth,\u201d\nkeeps a list of the pictures he\nhas played in since his debut in\nfilms. Th.e list is typed, in single\nfile, double spaced, on a continu\nous roll of paper. At present the\nroll measures exactly 6 feet 3\ninches in length.\nfl LAST TWO I MRS. FISKE I MATINEES AT\nTfBjIE\u2019C I I nHAnr\n1 IiYIILD I I TONIGHT AT\nI TODAY I \u201cBECKY SHARP\u201d I sharp\nI NATIONAL I\nw EP x m. ,8. I and week\nBRANDT present\nI E< ,uo\nI $S*\nI NOVEL/ CAS f\u00a3 50\nEXCITING/ By Era Kay Hint andjtartha Afgdiaoa\nENTERTAINING/ 8 M NEW >Q\u00ab\nWEEK BEG. MON. NOV. 10th\u2014SEATS TfiURS.\nGOOD NEWS/ GOOD NEWS\n\u2022WHAT'S AU THE SHOOTING FOR?*\nM. COHAN\nI \u2018T\u2019feTAVE RN*\nAND A CAPABLE CAST OF COHAN COMEDIANS\n/ffrr THE SEASON'S MOST NOTEWORTHY EVENT/\nMail Orders accepted. Nights: Orch.. $3.00; Bal., 88.50. 83.00 81.50; 8d Bal.,\nfl SI.OO. Wed. Sat. Mats.: Orch., $8.00; Bal., $1.50 A 81.00; 2d Bal., 50c.\nPlease enclose self-addressed and stamped envelope for retnrn of tieketa.\nI Week Beg. Sunday Night, Nov. 16th\nI S 3 GNttoring Scone*\n1000 Laugh*\n*1 Original Naw Ynrk\nI ppMAfcOM\n\u25a0K'M COMr *NY OF 1H INCLUOINg\n/MFI ll \"1 LT| Mtgr WILL MAHONEY\nwilliam demarest\nI *4 -A d flr&fo THE THREE SAILORS\n-^PP\u00bb e ,CANTOR_ Md\nII Mail Orders accepted. Nlahts: Oreh.. 84.40; Bal., 83.00 $8.00; 2d Bal.. U.M.\nSat. Mat.: Orch., $3.00; Bal.. $8.50. $2.00 a 1.50; 2d BaL. 81.00. Pleasa enclose\nI self-addressed and stamped envelope tor retam of tieketa.\nCONRAD NAGEL\nIN SCREEN\n\u2018DU BARRY*\nSome years ago a young man\nlistened anxiously in the wings of\nthe old Princess Theater in Des\nMoines, lowa. Fay Bainter, the\nstar, gave him his cue and Con\nrad Nagel made his stage debut.\nToday Conrad Nagel is a ft>\nmous screen favorite. His latest\nrole is opposite Norma Talmadge\nin her United Artists starring\npicture, \u201cDu Barry Woman of\nPassion,\u201d the intimate screen\nstory of the most famous siren\nof history, now on view at Loew\u2019s\nPalace Theater. s\nNagel was bom in Des Moines,\nthe son of Dr. Frank Nagel, a\nnoted composer and pianist. His\nmother was a concert singer.\nAs a young man looking for a\ncareer Nagel decided to become\nan architect. The nearest he\ngot to that ambition was a sum\nmer job laying bricks at a dollar\na day. He tried other vacation\njobs during his school days.\nOnce he was a key clerk, at an\nother time a telephone operator.\nHe graduated from Highland\nPark College with a degree. In\ncollege he had achieved a reputa-\ntion as an entertainer. That\npointed him toward the stage.\nAfter a season as a reader he\nplayed his first part with the\nPrincess Stock Company.\nDuring the var he served as\na seaman and upon his discharge\nin 1918 began his motion picture\ncareer in \u201cLittle Women.\u201d\nIn the Talmadge picture he'\njoins a cast of exceptional qual\nity, including William Famum,\nHobart Bosworth, Ullrich Haupt,\nAllison Skipworth, Edgar Norton\nand Maude Truex.\nCarmel Is Rich\nCarmel Myers, one of the cast\nin \u201cA Lady Surrenders,\u201d which\nwill be held for a second week at\nthe Rialto Theater, is one of the\nmost astute real estate operators\non the Western coast. It is said\nthat her income from real estate\ntransactions is nearly as large as\nthat received from her picture\nwork.\nITTLE 50<\nALL SEATS\nSTAGE and FILM Presentation for\nA STORY OF THE TRAFFIC\nIN SOULS\nUNGUARDED\nBare film C Startling\nFact. VJAIYXjJ Realirtle\nB T^ S MEM OMLY\n5","height":"30255","width":"24132"}}
